[{"id":"3703e790-85ab-4888-a218-3d32c470a377","component":"Text","data":{"content":"The solution, dynamic method builders, a dictionary and a cup of coffee for a long night of debugging. ","tag":"p","align":"left","weight":"regular","color":"","fontSize":"","fontFamily":"Inter, sans-serif","lineHeight":"","letterSpacing":"","marginBottom":"","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"1406f5a1-157e-4fb2-92bc-1ddc6993dc41","component":"Text","data":{"content":"The idea behind the solution is to enable serialization for any type while avoiding repeated allocations and the performance penalties associated with reflection. Reflection itself cannot be completely eliminated, but its impact can be minimized by limiting it to a single execution per .NET type.  Since these serializers operate in multi-threaded environments where race conditions are a real concern, a thread-safe cache was required. To address this, a private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, DynamicMethod> was introduced. This provides a shared, application-wide cache where generated serializers are stored per type. Because the dictionary has a static lifetime, the generated methods remain available for reuse and persist until the application shuts down.","tag":"p","align":"left","weight":"regular","color":"","fontSize":"","fontFamily":"Inter, sans-serif","lineHeight":"","letterSpacing":"","marginBottom":"","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"d81531b4-f2be-4014-921d-4872ca4f3982","component":"Text","data":{"content":"A dictionary was chosen over other storage structures because it provides amortized O(1) lookup performance. Internally, dictionaries distribute entries across buckets using the hash code of the key, allowing lookups to resolve directly to a small subset of candidates rather than performing a linear scan as would be required with an array or list. This significantly reduces lookup overhead as the number of cached serializers grows.","tag":"p","align":"left","weight":"regular","color":"","fontSize":"","fontFamily":"Inter, sans-serif","lineHeight":"","letterSpacing":"","marginBottom":"","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"e6734b15-d923-4d59-9425-0194f4b5690c","component":"Text","data":{"content":"Now that we had our data container, the next thing was generating the serializer, so first, we created a dynamic method.","tag":"p","align":"left","weight":"regular","color":"","fontSize":"","fontFamily":"Inter, sans-serif","lineHeight":"","letterSpacing":"","marginBottom":"","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"2d895a9f-b16d-4f33-b077-12fb30220400","component":"CodeBlock","data":{"code":"using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Reflection;
using System.Reflection.Emit;

namespace JsonExample
{
    /// <summary>
    /// This is only a light example to demonstrate how this is built, there
    /// are cases not covered here, but this handles a large majority, in our
    /// original implementation we also added role checks for field rules, this 
    /// is more just an example to demonstrate proficiency. 
    /// </summary>
    public static class Json
    {
        /// <summary>
        /// Holds the types, this means once the serializer has been generated, 
        /// we can invoke it every time it's needed for a dramatic improvement 
        /// in performance, less GC pressure, less heap usage too.
        /// </summary>
        private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, Action<object, StringWriter>> _serializers = new();

        /// <summary>
        /// Takes the input type, and a writer and serializes 
        /// the given input.
        /// </summary>
        /// <typeparam name="T"></typeparam>
        /// <param name="obj"></param>
        /// <param name="writer"></param>
        public static void Serialize<T>(T obj, StringWriter writer)
        {
            // for an easy win, 
            // regardless of the
            // values type, if its
            // null, it takes the fast
            // path
            if (obj is null)
            {
                writer.Write("null");
                return;
            }

            // next, in most of our entities
            // string was the most common
            // field type, so we check string
            // first, if so, we have another fast exit.
            // string is also nullable, so
            // there's the potential the execution
            // hits the above branch completely skipping
            // this. 
            if (obj is string stringValue)
            {
                writer.Write("\"");
                // this was also escaped 
                // properly in the original
                // implementation.
                writer.Write(stringValue);
                writer.Write("\"");
                return;
            }

            // the next most common data
            // type was unsignted integer
            // that came next, this then meant
            // the most common data types had a hot
            // route.
            if (obj is uint intValue)
            {
                writer.Write(intValue);
                return;
            }

            // bool was used next, this was mostly
            // for flags, which a lot of the time 
            // never checked beyond the backend,
            // these were often omitted with
            // [JsonIgnore]
            if (obj is bool boolValue)
            {
                writer.Write(boolValue ? "true" : "false");
                return;
            }

            // next was ulongs, commonly used for
            //  bitwise flags, these are
            // great for branchess logic, you can
            // pack 64 flags in a single ulong, 
            // you can even use a ulong[] array
            // should you need more flags.
            if (obj is ulong ulongValue)
            {
                writer.Write(ulongValue);
                return;
            }

            // Dictionaries implement IEnumerable
            // which means if we allow the if branch
            // below to handle dictionaries, which would
            // be incorrect, as Dictionary<string,K> is 
            // equivalent to Record<string,K> in JSON.
            if (obj is IDictionary dictionary)
            {
                writer.Write("{");

                bool first = true;

                foreach (DictionaryEntry entry in dictionary)
                {
                    if (!first)
                        writer.Write(",");

                    writer.Write("\"");
                    writer.Write(entry.Key);
                    writer.Write("\":");

                    Serialize(entry.Value, writer);

                    first = false;
                }

                writer.Write("}");
                return;
            }

            // Now we check for collections
            // these are output as arrays, 
            // we checked string earlier, so
            // no chance of string being here.
            if (obj is IEnumerable enumerable)
            {
                writer.Write("[");

                bool first = true;

                foreach (var item in enumerable)
                {
                    if (!first)
                        writer.Write(",");

                    Serialize(item, writer);
                    first = false;
                }

                writer.Write("]");
                return;
            }

            // if we've reached here, its an 
            // object that needs to be serialized 
            // by a generated serializer
            var type = obj.GetType();

            // check first see if we can get
            // the serializer from cache.
            if (_serializers.TryGetValue(type, out var serializer))
            {
                serializer(obj!, writer);
                return;
            }

            // here it doesn't exist, this 
            // is where we pay the reflection
            // fee, but we only pay it once per type.
            serializer = CreateSerializer<T>();
            serializer(obj!, writer);
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// The method responsible for the actual creation
        /// of the serializer.
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="type"></param>
        /// <returns></returns>
        private static Action<T, StringWriter> CreateSerializer<T>()
        {
            // first, this is a generic class
            // we can collect the target type.
            var type = typeof(T);

            // then we instantiate a new
            // dynamic method, the arguments
            // here are as provided
            var method = new DynamicMethod(
                // method name, not really used
                // but still needs to be satisfied.
                "serializer_" + type.Name,
                // the return type, the 
                // serializer doesn't return
                // anything, it uses a pooled 
                // writer.
                typeof(void),

                // then we specify the parameter types
                // they don't need labels, as labels are
                // purely a language construct, the
                // arg at the index has type informtion, 
                // but the parameters are converted to
                // Ldarg_{index}
                [typeof(T), typeof(StringWriter)],    
                restrictedSkipVisibility: true
            );

            // then we get the ILGenerator
            // this is an amazingly powerful
            // tool, but it is also very cruel.
            // IL gives you an insane 
            // level of performance, but
            // debugging is often migraine
            // inducing. 
            var il = method.GetILGenerator();

            // then we collect the method we're 
            // wanting to call, 
            var writeString = typeof(StringWriter).GetMethod(nameof(StringWriter.Write), [typeof(string)]);

            // Ldarg_1 loads the argument
            // passed to the serializer.
            // the stack here is [argValue]
            // the argValue is 
            // the writer
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);

            // here you can use Ldstr for
            // a string, or you could load
            // a char and have a char override.
            // the stack here is [writer, "{"]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldstr, "{");

            // Then we use Callvirt, we dont use
            // OpCodes.Call as that's for static
            // methods. Calling this consumes a
            // single item off the stack since 
            // WriteString only takes a single
            // argument, the stack is LIFO, 
            // so now, the stack looks like:
            // the stack here is [argValue], 
            // as we consumed the "{" calling
            // WriteString on writer, the stack
            // is now balanced, you would 
            // conventionally have to handle return
            // values, but WriteString is void
            // which means we're not expecting a
            // return value. 
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, writeString);

            // keep track of "first" to 
            // ensure ',' are appended 
            // correctly, the responsibility
            // of CreateField and CreateProperty
            // is to just create the JSON for 
            // the value they're passed.
            bool first = true;

            // notice here we don't use LINQ, 
            // LINQ adds delegate capture, 
            // phantom enumerables, and GC pressure. 
            // we use a foreach loop, we avoid any if
            // statements in here to take advantage
            // of RyuJits aggressive inlining. 
            // it also helps with branch prediction
            foreach (var field in type.GetFields(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance))
            {
                // create field only needs to know of
                // the IL generator - to write the IL emission to.
                // the field to pull required context for IL to 
                // emit based off types etc... 
                // we also use ref first here...
                // we do this because we want to track
                // when the first field has been added
                // so every continuing field inserts a ","
                // to ensure valid JSON, we don't use "in"
                // as we're modifying the value.
                CreateField(il, field, type, ref first);
            }

            foreach (var property in type.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Public | BindingFlags.Instance))
            {
                // For properties, we check CanRead because a property might be write-only
                // (i.e., it has a setter but no getter). Attempting to serialize such a property
                // would fail because there is no value to read.
                // 
                // Fields, on the other hand, are always directly readable if they are returned
                // by GetFields with the appropriate binding flags, so there is no equivalent
                // CanRead check needed for fields.
                if (!property.CanRead)
                {
                    continue;
                }
                // then if it can be read, lets ensure it can be serialized.
                CreateProperty(il, property, type, ref first);
            }

            // the stack at this point is all balanced, 
            // next we need to load the writer again
            // to write the closing '}' to keep the JSON
            // valid.
            // the stack here is [writer]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);
            // push a string before consuming
            // [writer, "}"]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldstr, "}");
            // the stack here is now emptied
            // we don't collect anything from
            // writeString as its a void method.
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, writeString);

            // here we're done with the method,
            // so we add return, and this is then
            // a valid IL method.
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ret);

            // Compile the DynamicMethod into a delegate and cache it for the type.
            // Using a delegate instead of MethodInfo.Invoke avoids reflection overhead,
            // eliminates per-call array allocation for arguments, and allows the serializer
            // to be invoked as a normal method for maximum performance.
            var del = (Action<T, StringWriter>)method.CreateDelegate(typeof(Action<T, StringWriter>));

            // then we cache it.
            _serializers[type] = del;

            // then we return the delegate.
            return del;
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// This creates a field in the IL Generator.
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="il"></param>
        /// <param name="field"></param>
        /// <param name="declaringType"></param>
        /// <param name="first"></param>
        private static void CreateField(ILGenerator il, FieldInfo field, Type declaringType, ref bool first)
        {
            // we get the string write method. 
            var writeString = typeof(StringWriter).GetMethod(nameof(StringWriter.Write), [typeof(string)]);

            // if its not the first
            // we need to append a ',' 
            // this keeps the JSON valid.
            if (!first)
            {
                // Ldarg_1, (the writer)
                // stack [writer]
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);
                // load the comma string
                // stack [writer, ","]
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldstr, ",");
                // call the write string
                // stack []
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, writeString);
            }

            // now we mark false, so all subsequent items 
            // all require a comma.
            first = false;

            // Ldarg_1, (the writer)
            // stack [writer]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);
            // emit the field name
            // stack [writer, fieldName]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldstr, $"\"{field.Name}\":");
            // emit callVirt
            // stack []
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, writeString);

            // load arg 0 (which is the object)
            // stack [object]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_0);
            // then we cast to the declaring type.
            // and pushes it back onto the stack.
            // stack [object]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Castclass, declaringType);
            // then we load the value of the field onto 
            // the stack
            // stack [object, value]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldfld, field);

            // if its a value type, it needs
            // boxing. 
            if (field.FieldType.IsValueType)
            {
                // here we box it to the base
                // class of "object" (System.Object)
                // stack [object, fldValue]
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Box, field.FieldType);
            }

            // then we load the writer onto the stack
            // stack before: [fldValue(object)]
            // stack after:  [fldValue(object), writer]
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);

            // then we get the Serialize<T> method
            var serialize = typeof(Json)
                .GetMethod(nameof(Serialize))
                .MakeGenericMethod(field.FieldType);

            // call Serialize<T>
            // Serialize<T>(T obj, StringWriter writer) expects:
            //   stack: [obj (field value), writer]
            // after the call, stack is empty
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Call, serialize);
        }

        /// <summary>
        /// This does the same as CreateField, so not going 
        /// to add any documentation to this method.
        /// </summary>
        /// <param name="il"></param>
        /// <param name="property"></param>
        /// <param name="declaringType"></param>
        /// <param name="first"></param>
        private static void CreateProperty(ILGenerator il, PropertyInfo property, Type declaringType, ref bool first)
        {
            var writeString = typeof(StringWriter).GetMethod(nameof(StringWriter.Write), new[] { typeof(string) });

            if (!first)
            {
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldstr, ",");
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, writeString);
            }

            first = false;

            // Write key
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldstr, $"\"{property.Name}\":");
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, writeString);

            // Load property value
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_0);
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Castclass, declaringType);
            il.Emit(OpCodes.Callvirt, property.GetGetMethod());

            if (property.PropertyType.IsValueType)
                il.Emit(OpCodes.Box, property.PropertyType);

            il.Emit(OpCodes.Ldarg_1);

            var serialize = typeof(Json)
                .GetMethod(nameof(Serialize))
                .MakeGenericMethod(property.PropertyType);

            il.Emit(OpCodes.Call, serialize);
        }
    }
}","language":"csharp","filename":"Json.cs","showCopy":"true","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"ab3385be-6db2-4de9-9a10-24e22d8926fc","component":"Divider","data":{"variant":"spacer","size":"md","label":"","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"63a8c0fd-586f-4f48-9d06-ecce777ece8f","component":"Text","data":{"content":"By generating the serializer in IL and compiling it into a delegate, the cost of reflection is amortized to a single per-type setup. After the first serialization, the delegate executes like a normal method call, eliminating the repeated overhead of PropertyInfo.GetValue or MethodInfo.Invoke. Arguments are passed directly on the evaluation stack, and reference types are handled without boxing. Value types, however, are boxed in this example when passed through the generic path, which adds minor allocations. Even so, this design allows the serializer to operate at near-native speed while supporting arbitrary object shapes, collections, and nested structures.","tag":"p","align":"left","weight":"regular","color":"","fontSize":"","fontFamily":"Inter, sans-serif","lineHeight":"","letterSpacing":"","marginBottom":"","className":""},"children":[]},{"id":"0065065e-8bab-42ec-b487-3f5af6c180b9","component":"Text","data":{"content":"In practice, these IL-based serializers achieve orders of magnitude higher throughput than reflection-based approaches, often handling millions of objects per second once JIT warmup is complete. Further performance improvements and reduction of GC pressure can be achieved by special-casing primitives to avoid boxing and by using pooled StringWriter buffers or ArrayPool<char>. This allows serialization to occur allocation-free on the hot path, resulting in predictable low-latency behavior even in high-throughput, multithreaded environments.","tag":"p","align":"left","weight":"regular","color":"","fontSize":"","fontFamily":"Inter, sans-serif","lineHeight":"","letterSpacing":"","marginBottom":"","className":""},"children":[]}]
